In the figure, the outer equilateral triangle has area $36$, the inner equilateral triangle has area $4$, and the three trapezoids have areas in the ratio 3:2:1. What is the area of the smallest trapezoid?
{{DGM:478e9217cfa81dd5}}
$\textbf{(A)}\ 4.33 \qquad \textbf{(B)}\ 5.33 \qquad  \textbf{(C)}\ 6.33 \qquad \textbf{(D)}\ 7.33 \qquad \textbf{(E)}\ 8.33$

An eight-digit number (base 10) is ultra-squarish if it satisfies the following conditions:
(i) none of its digits are zero;
(ii) it is a perfect square;
(iii) the first two digits, the second pair of two digits, the third pair of digits, and the fourth pair of digits of the number are all perfect squares when considered as two-digit numbers.
How many ultra-squarish numbers are there?
$\text{(A)} \ 0 \qquad  \text{(B)} \ 2 \qquad  \text{(C)} \ 4 \qquad  \text{(D)} \ 8 \qquad  \text{(E)} \ 18$

Square $ABCD$ in the coordinate plane has vertices at $A(1,1), B(-1,1), C(-1,-1),$ and $D(1,-1).$ Consider the following five transformations:
- $L,$ a rotation of $90^{\circ}$ counterclockwise around the origin;
- $R,$ a rotation of $90^{\circ}$ clockwise around the origin;
- $H,$ a reflection across the $x$-axis;
- $V,$ a reflection across the $y$-axis;
- $S,$ a shift such that $S(x, y) = (x+2, y+2)$.
Each of these transformations maps the square into a new position. How many sequences of $30$ transformations chosen from $\{L, R, H, V, S\}$ will send all of the labeled vertices back to their original positions?
A. $4^{30} + 2^7$
B. $4^{29} + 2^{15}$
C. $4^{30} + 2^{15}$
D. $4^{31} + 2^{16}$
E. $4^{32} + 2^{14}$
